    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the intro. Some of my students might ask why we call it \"substantive\" instead of just \"due process\" though. Could you add a bit more detail explaining the difference between that and just following legal procedures? I want them to understand why the \"substance\" of the law matters so much for these rights.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Due process\" simply means the government must follow fair procedures—like giving you a hearing before taking away your rights. Substantive due process, however, looks at the *content* or \"substance\" of the law itself to determine if it violates fundamental rights, regardless of how fairly it was enacted. This distinction is vital because it allows the courts to strike down laws that are procedurally sound but fundamentally unjust or oppressive to individual liberty. It is the substantive element that truly protects core freedoms from legislative overreach.",
      "source": "target",
